<para id="para-00001"><emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis>-Amino acids can be synthesized in the laboratory using some of the reactions discussed in previous chapters. One of the oldest methods of <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis>-amino acid synthesis begins with <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis> bromination of a carboxylic acid by treatment with Br<sub>2</sub> and PBr<sub>3</sub> (the Hell–Volhard–Zelinskii reaction; <link document="m00260"/>). S<sub>N</sub>2 substitution of the <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis>-bromo acid with ammonia then yields an <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis>-amino acid.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00001">
<media alt="An illustration shows a reaction wherein 4-methylpentanoic acid reacts with green Br2 green PBr3 and pink water molecule to form 2-Bromo-4-methylpentanoic acid that further reacts with blue ammonia “excess” to form (R S)-Leucine (45%). The structure of 4-methylpentanoic acid shows a methyl group bonded to a methine group bonded to another methyl at the top the methine group is further bonded to two methylene groups bonded to a carbonyl group (pink oxygen) whose carbon is bonded to a pink hydroxyl group. 2-Bromo-4-methylpentanoic acid shows a methyl group bonded to a methine group bonded to another methyl at the top the methine group is bonded to a methylene group bonded to a methine group bonded to a green bromine at the bottom the methine is bonded to a carbonyl group (pink oxygen) whose carbon is bonded to a pink hydroxyl group. (R S)-Leucine (45%) shows a methyl group bonded to a methine group bonded to another methyl at the top the methine group is bonded to a methylene group bonded to a methine group bonded to a blue ammonium ion at the bottom the methine is bonded to a carbonyl group (pink oxygen) whose carbon is bonded to a pink oxygen anion.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_26_03_001.jpg"/></media>
</figure>
