<section id="sect-00002">
<title>The Amidomalonate Synthesis</title>
<para id="para-00003">A more general method for preparation of <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis>-amino acids is the <emphasis effect="italics">amidomalonate synthesis,</emphasis> a straightforward extension of the malonic ester synthesis (<link document="m00263"/>). The reaction begins with the conversion of diethyl acetamidomalonate into an enolate ion by treatment with base, followed by S<sub>N</sub>2 alkylation with a primary alkyl halide. Hydrolysis of both the amide protecting group and the esters occurs when the alkylated product is warmed with aqueous acid, and decarboxylation then takes place to yield an <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis>-amino acid. For example, aspartic acid can be prepared from ethyl bromoacetate, BrCH<sub>2</sub>CO<sub>2</sub>Et:</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00002">
<media alt="An illustration shows a reaction wherein diethyl acetamidomalonate reacts with sodium ethoxide and green BrCH2CO2Et to form an intermediate compound that reacts with a hydronium ion and heat to form (R S)-Aspartic acid (55%). Diethyl acetamidomalonate shows a blue hydrogen bonded to a blue nitrogen bonded to a carbon at the top which is bonded to a hydrogen on the left and two pink ethyl acetate groups on the right and top; the blue nitrogen is further bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a methyl group. The intermediate compound shows a blue hydrogen bonded to a blue nitrogen bonded to a carbon at the top which is bonded to a green methylene group bonded to a green ethyl acetate group on the left and two pink ethyl acetate groups on the right and top; the blue nitrogen is further bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a methyl group. (R S)-Aspartic acid shows a green carboxylate ion bonded to a green methylene group bonded to a methine group bonded to a blue ammonium ion at the bottom and a pink carboxylate ion on the right.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_26_03_002.jpg"/></media>
</figure>
</section>
